    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm editing a biology paper and i keep seeing a lot of passive voice. can u explain how to spot it and how i should actually fix it so the sentences are more direct?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The passive voice can be a bit sneaky, but spotting it is relatively easy. It's often characterized by the use of a verb form that doesn't clearly indicate the doer of the action, such as \"was found,\" \"was discovered,\" or \"was observed.\" To identify passive voice, look for phrases like \"was\" or \"were\" followed by the verb, or try to rephrase the sentence to make the doer of the action more explicit.\n\nFor example, \"The experiment was conducted by a team of researchers\" can be rewritten as \"A team of researchers conducted the experiment.\" This change makes the doer of the action (the researchers) more clear and direct, rather than relying on the passive voice.\n\nAnother way to spot passive voice is to ask yourself, \"Who is performing the action?\" If the answer isn't immediately clear, it's likely the sentence is in passive voice. And don't worry, it's not a death sentence – with a bit of rewriting, you can make your sentences more direct and engaging.",
